et al. [26], Hu and Krishnamachari [49], Lee et al. [70], Shao and Zhang [126] use cross entropy to train bottleneck-injected DNN models in end-to-end manners (Fig. 3), Matsubara et al. [91] empirically show that these methods cause a larger accuracy loss in complex tasks such as ImageNet dataset [120] compared to other more advanced techniques, including knowledge distillation.

Knowledge distillation
Complex DNN models are usually trained to learn parameters for discriminating between a large number of classes (e.g., 1, 000 in ImageNet dataset), and are often overparameterized. Knowledge distillation (KD) [3, 46, 78] is a training scheme to address this problem, and trains a DNN model (called ‚Äústudent‚Äù) using additional signals from a pretrained DNN model (called ‚Äúteacher‚Äù and often larger than the student). In standard cross entropy-based training ‚Äì that is, using ‚Äúhard targets‚Äù (e.g., one-hot vectors) ‚Äì we face a side-effect that the trained models assign probabilities to all of the incorrect classes. From the relative probabilities of incorrect classes, we can see how large models tend to generalize.
As illustrated in Fig. 4, by distilling the knowledge from a pretrained complex model (teacher), a student model can be more generalized and avoid overfitting to the training dataset, using the outputs of the teacher model as ‚Äúsoft targets‚Äù in addition to the hard targets [46].

LKD (yÀÜS, yÀÜT, y) = ùõº Ltask (yÀÜS, y) + (1 ‚àí ùõº)ùúè2KL q(yÀÜS), p(yÀÜT) ,

(3)

where ùõº is a balancing factor (hyperparameter) between hard target (left term) and soft target (right
term) losses, and ùúè is another hyperparameter called temperature to soften the outputs of teacher
and student models in Eq. (4). Ltask is a task-specific loss function, and it is a cross entropy loss in image classification tasks i.e., Ltask = LCE. KL is the Kullback-Leibler divergence function, where q(yÀÜS) and p(yÀÜT) are probability distributions of student and teacher models for an input x, that is, q(yÀÜS) = [q1 (yÀÜS), ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ , q|C | (yÀÜS)] and p(yÀÜT) = [p1 (yÀÜS), ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ , p|ùê∂ | (yÀÜT)]:

