matches a widely known trend in knowledge distillation reported in Ba and Caruana [3]. However, similar to cross entropy, the knowledge distillation is still not aware of bottlenecks we introduce to DNN models and may result in significant accuracy loss as suggested by Matsubara et al. [91].
Reconstruction-based training
As illustrated in Fig. 5, Choi et al. [14], Jankowski et al. [57], Sbai et al. [124], Yao et al. [164] inject Autoencoder (AE) models into existing DNN models, and train the injected components by minimizing the reconstruction error. First manually an intermediate layer in a DNN model (say its ùëóth layer) is chosen, and the output of the ùëóth layer zùëó is fed to the encoder fenc whose role is to compress zùëó . The encoder‚Äôs output zenc is a compressed representation, i.e., bottleneck to be transferred to edge server and the following decoder fdec decompresses the compressed representation and returns zdec. As the decoder is designed to reconstruct zùëó , its output zdec should share the same dimensionality with zùëó . Then, the injected AE are trained by minimizing the following reconstruction loss:

